        "excerpt": "Those men said to him, 'Though we are unclean because of the dead person, why are we restrained from presenting the offering of the LORD at its appointed time among the sons of Israel?' Moses therefore said to them, 'Wait, and I will listen to what the LORD will command concerning you.'",
        "body": "The brevity of this passage belies its importance. Three verses introduce a pastoral crisis that will generate one of the Pentateuch's most significant legal supplements. Some men — probably a small group, unnamed and uncounted — are in a condition of ritual impurity from contact with a corpse. Leviticus 21-22 and Numbers 19 are unambiguous: such defilement requires a seven-day purification process (Numbers 19:11-12) and disqualifies a person from sacred assembly. These men cannot observe Passover. The law excludes them.\n\nTheir response is a model of pastoral integrity. They do not complain about the law's harshness, do not quietly absent themselves, do not find a workaround. They bring a pointed theological question to Moses and Aaron: 'Why are we restrained from presenting the offering of the LORD at its appointed time among the sons of Israel?' The question is not a protest — it is a theology-driven inquiry. They identify the sacrifice as 'the LORD's offering,' they name the appointed time as the operative standard, and they locate their grief in exclusion from the community's defining act. They want to worship; the law appears to prevent it. What should be done?\n\nMoses's response is one of the Old Testament's great models of humble leadership: 'Wait, and I will listen to what the LORD will command concerning you.' He does not reach for a precedent. He does not apply analogical reasoning. He does not put his own wisdom on display. He stands still and listens. The verb 'listen' (*shama*) here is covenantal: it is the posture of the servant before the commanding Lord. Moses cannot solve this; God must answer it. This is not weak leadership — it is exactly the kind of leadership the cloud-guided life (vv. 15-23) requires of the whole nation: move when God moves, speak when God speaks, wait when God has not yet spoken.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Gara* (restrained/excluded, v. 7) means to diminish, to withhold, to prevent access. The men feel the exclusion as a diminishment of their standing in the covenant community. *Amad* (wait, v. 8) means to stand, to remain in place — Moses commands a posture, not merely a pause. *Shama* (listen/hear) is the foundational covenantal verb: the Shema (*Shema Yisrael*, 'Hear, O Israel') — the same verb. Moses will do what Israel is commanded to do: hear."
