        "excerpt": "If any one of you or of your generations becomes unclean because of a dead person, or is on a distant journey, he may, however, observe the Passover to the LORD.",
        "body": "God's answer to Moses is one of the most grace-saturated legal rulings in the Torah. The question was about a small group of unclean men at Sinai. God's answer covers them, every future generation, and every Israelite — unclean or traveling — who finds themselves unable to observe on the appointed day. The legislation is permanent ('of your generations,' v. 10), universal in scope, and specific in detail. The second Passover is not a reduced observance — unleavened bread, bitter herbs, no bone broken, nothing left until morning (vv. 11-12). The same requirements apply. God has not lowered the standard; He has extended the provision.\n\nVerse 13 is the necessary counterpart. The man who is **clean** and **not on a journey** — who has no hindrance whatsoever — and still neglects to observe Passover shall be **cut off from his people**. The penalty (*karat*, excision from the covenant community) is the Torah's most severe sanction, applied in Exodus 12:15, 19 to the Passover feast itself. The juxtaposition of verses 10-12 (grace for the genuinely hindered) and verse 13 (penalty for the deliberately negligent) is the chapter's sharpest ethical distinction. God makes extraordinary provision for those whom circumstances prevent from worshipping. He holds fully accountable those whom nothing prevents.\n\nVerse 14 extends the legislation to the alien sojourner (*ger*) — and does so with stunning brevity. One verse, no discussion, no qualifications: the alien who wants to observe Passover to the LORD does so under the same statute as the native-born Israelite. 'You shall have one statute, both for the alien and for the native of the land.' The Passover — the feast of Israel's rescue from oppression — is opened to the very category of person who in Egypt was the alien, the outsider, the one without standing. This is not assimilation; the alien must observe the feast as prescribed. But it is full inclusion: the God of Israel is not a tribal deity.\n\nThe canonical trajectory of verse 14 is significant. Isaiah 56:6-7 reads this provision eschatologically — the foreigner who holds fast to the covenant will come to God's holy mountain. Jesus fulfills this in the Last Supper (which is explicitly a Passover, Luke 22:15) by opening the covenant meal to those who were gentiles. Paul reads the church as the community where 'there is neither Jew nor Greek' (Galatians 3:28), precisely because the covenant has always been open to those who come in faith. Numbers 9:14 is not a footnote; it is a seed of the New Testament's broadest claim.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Karat* (cut off, v. 13) is the covenant excision formula — used at least 35 times in the Pentateuch for covenant violations. *Chet* (sin, v. 13) — the guilt of the violation rests on the individual; no communal covering is offered for willful neglect. *Ger* (alien, v. 14) — resident foreigner; the same figure whom Leviticus 19:34 commands Israel to love as themselves. *Ezrach* (native of the land, v. 14) — the full citizen; placed in exact parallel with the *ger* under *chuqqah echad* (one statute)."
